'''Llŷr''' ({{lang-cy|Llŷr Llediaith}} ({{IPA-cy|ˈɬɨːr ˈɬɛdjaiθ}}); ''Lleddiaith'' meaning "half-speech"<ref>{{Harvnb|Bromwich|1961}}, triads #8 and #52</ref> or "half-language"<ref>{{Harvnb|Mackillop|1998}}</ref>) is a figure in [[Welsh mythology]], probably originally a deity, probably derived from Irish [[Lir|Ler]] ("the Sea"), father of ''[[Manannán mac Lir]]''.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mackillop|1998}}, "Llŷr is often assumed to be borrowed from the Irish Lir, the patronym of the sea-god Manannán</ref> 
Other than his progeny and odd tidbits, his identity remains obscure.

Llŷr appears as the father of [[Brân the Blessed|Brân]], [[Branwen|Brânwen]] and [[Manawydan]] by [[Penarddun]] in the [[Four Branches of the Mabinogi#Branwen, Daughter of Llyr|''Branwen, Daughter of Llyr'']], the Second Branch of the ''[[Mabinogion|Mabinogi]]''.<ref name=jones>{{Harvnb|Jones|Jones|1949}}, New Revised ed. 1993, p. 21, "Bendigeidfran son of Llŷr was crowned king.. His two brothers on the mother's side (Nisien and Efnisien) were sons of Euroswydd by his mother Penarddun."</ref>

The [[Welsh Triads]] states that Llŷr was imprisoned by [[Euroswydd]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Bromwich|1961}}, triad #52</ref> and presumbably, Penarddun consequently married Euroswydd,<ref>{{Harvnb|Mountain|1998}} Celt. Enc. vol. 4, p. 930, "Penarddun then married Euroswydd and bore his children Nissyen and Evnissyen"</ref> giving birth by Euroswydd to her two younger sons, [[Nisien]] and [[Efnisien]], as stated in the [[Four Branches of the Mabinogi#Branwen, Daughter of Llyr|Second Branch]].<ref name=jones/>

[[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[King Lear]]'' is based on material taken secondhand (through [[Holinshed]]) from [[Geoffrey of Monmouth]]'s mythical king [[Leir of Britain|King Leir]], who has often been connected, but is likely unrelated, to Llŷr.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mackillop|1998}}, "Many trace Shakespear's.. Lear to Llŷr, but the route is tortuous; Shakespeare drew from Holinshed's Chronicles (1577)", etc.</ref>

